Nov 8 2009 	Good Not Great	Let me begin my review by saying my wife absolutely loved this hotel and cannot believe I have anything negative to say about it so take that for what it's worth. The hotel itself is in the absolute best location in NYC. It's location effectively provides for a private road in front which allows for easy entry and exit into your vehicle (if you drive) or for catching a cab (compared with The Ritz, The Peninsula, St. Regis and Mandarin, all of which are on very busy streets and have no place to park). I found the room to be clean although I was not a fan of the antiquated furnishings and retro gold bathroom fixtures. The butler service was very spotty. I called for a restocking of the wet bar and it took over three (3) hours for this to be taken care of. During our stay the hotel was having problems with it's television service and so we were without several television stations. Due to the size of the hotel, it is hard to expect a level of service whereby the doormen recall your name etc., as you might if you are accustomed to staying at a Four Seasons, Ritz, Mandarin or small boutique properties. All in all, The Plaza is an institution and for that, I am glad I stayed. However, compared to the Four Seasons Jackson Hole, Mandarin Oriental DC, Beverly Wilshire, Arrabelle at Vail, Four Seasons Miami, or King Edward Hotel Toronto, it doesn't even come close.	
Nov 6 2009 	Great Hotel - Excellent Location	Of course, one must realise that today's Plaza Hotel is not the legend it once was, as most of the hotel was converted to private apartments during the recent refit. What is left, however, is still magnificent, both as a hotel, conference centre and function venue. Certainly, some facilities are not what they used to be, nor are they as good as one might expect for a hotel of this stature - the breakfast area, squeezed into the corner of the lobby being but one example. The rooms, however, are extremely comfortable, well decorated and provided with every modern amenity that one could wish for including a huge flat screen TV and a marble lined bathroom. In my experience, service was also top rate. Add to this its central location at the south end of Central Park on 5th Ave. where it is equidistant between the Guggenheim, the Mettropolitan Museum, MoMA and Broadway theatres, and a stones throw from the high end 5th Avenue stores and it's appeal is obvious. Cost? Well, that's high, but in a place like this that's what you pay. All in all - excellent.	
